  "prompt": "Which enzyme uses both NAD+ and NADP+ as a coenzyme?",
  "response": "**Glutamate Dehydrogenase** is an example of an enzyme that can utilize both NAD\u207a and NADP\u207a as coenzymes. This enzyme plays a crucial role in amino acid metabolism by catalyzing the reversible oxidative deamination of glutamate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. The ability to use both cofactors allows glutamate dehydrogenase to participate flexibly in various metabolic pathways, depending on the cell's redox state and specific metabolic needs.\n\n**Key Points:**\n- **Function:** Converts glutamate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate (and vice versa) with the concomitant conversion of NAD\u207a to NADH or NADP\u207a to NADPH.\n- **Versatility:** The dual coenzyme usage allows the enzyme to function in both catabolic and anabolic processes.\n- **Biological Significance:** Plays a role in nitrogen metabolism and the regulation of the cellular redox state.\n\n**Other Enzymes:** While glutamate dehydrogenase is a prominent example, most enzymes are typically specific to either NAD\u207a or NADP\u207a. However, the flexibility of glutamate dehydrogenase makes it unique in its ability to interact with both coenzymes.\n\n**References:**\n- Berg, J. M., Tymoczko, J. L., & Stryer, L. (2002). *Biochemistry*. W.H. Freeman.\n- Lehninger, A. L., Nelson, D. L., & Cox, M. M. (2008). *Principles of Biochemistry*. W.H. Freeman.\n\n**Summary:**  \nGlutamate dehydrogenase is the enzyme that can use both NAD\u207a and NADP\u207a as coenzymes.",
